# Enterprise Engineering Standards

Every change must be written as if it will serve thousands of concurrent users and be maintained by a large team.

## Architecture

- Strict separation of concerns: routes → services → repositories/models
- Never put business logic in route handlers — delegate to service layer
- All cross-cutting concerns (auth, logging, error handling) use middleware, not inline code
- Design for horizontal scaling — no in-memory state that can't be externalized (use Redis)

## Backend (Python / FastAPI)

- Type-annotate every function signature (params and return types)
- Use Pydantic schemas for all request/response validation — never pass raw dicts across boundaries
- Use dependency injection (`Depends()`) for DB sessions, auth, and services
- Async endpoints by default (`async def`) — sync only when calling blocking I/O with proper threadpool
- All DB queries go through SQLAlchemy models — no raw SQL strings
- Use Alembic for every schema change — never modify tables manually
- Environment config via `pydantic-settings` — no hardcoded secrets or connection strings
- Structured error responses with consistent status codes and error shapes

## Frontend (React / TypeScript)

- Strict TypeScript — no `any`, no `@ts-ignore`, no `as` type casts unless truly unavoidable
- Every component prop gets an explicit interface/type
- State: Zustand stores for global state, local `useState`/refs for ephemeral UI state
- Keep components small and composable — max ~150 lines per file before splitting
- Memoize expensive renders (`React.memo`, `useMemo`, `useCallback`) where measurable
- All API calls go through service modules in `services/` — never `fetch()` inline in components

## Data Layer

- Every DB table gets proper indexes on foreign keys and frequently queried columns
- Use UUIDs for primary keys (avoids enumeration attacks, enables distributed ID generation)
- All timestamps are UTC with timezone (`TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE`)
- Soft-delete pattern where data recovery may be needed
- Migrations must be reversible (include downgrade steps)

## Error Handling

- Backend: raise typed exceptions, catch in middleware, return structured JSON errors
- Frontend: global error boundary + per-request error handling in service layer
- Never swallow errors silently — log or surface every caught exception

## Security

- JWT tokens in HTTP-only cookies or Authorization header — never localStorage
- Validate and sanitize all user input at the boundary (Pydantic on backend, zod/schemas on frontend)
- CORS restricted to explicit origins
- Rate limiting on auth endpoints

## Naming Conventions

- Backend: `snake_case` for files, functions, variables; `PascalCase` for classes and Pydantic models
- Frontend: `PascalCase` for components and types; `camelCase` for functions, variables, hooks
- Test files mirror source files: `auth_service.py` → `test_auth_service.py`, `App.tsx` → `App.test.tsx`
